● I've read it. Here's my understanding and how I'd map it onto the harness.

  What OpenRouter's "Fusion" actually is
  A three-stage pipeline run as one call:
  1. Parallel dispatch — the same prompt goes to a panel of models simultaneously.
  2. Judge analysis — a judge model reads all panel responses and produces a structured analysis: consensus points, contradictions, partial coverage,
  unique insights, blind spots. (Note: it doesn't just pick a winner — it maps the disagreement.)
  3. Synthesis — the calling model writes the final answer grounded in the judge's analysis.

  The result that matters most for you: fusing Opus 4.8 with itself went 58.8% → 65.5%. So the gain isn't only from mixing different vendors — the
  judge+synthesis step itself is what drives most of the lift. That's the key, because it means a Claude-only beast-mode (Opus panel + Opus judge) is a
  legitimate, big chunk of the benefit without needing GPT/Gemini keys.

  What you're describing ("beast-mode")

  A harness mode where the main Opus 4.8 in your terminal doesn't act directly. Before any decision/action, it:
  - fans the question out to 2 Opus 4.8 subagents (the panel),
  - a 3rd Opus subagent judges/synthesizes their outputs,
  - and the synthesized result comes back to the main Claude, which then acts on it.

  So you're applying Fusion at the control-loop level — turning the main agent into the "calling model" and inserting a panel→judge gate in front of its
  actions.

  The honest tension (this shapes the design)

  "Every action and every decision" through 3 Opus calls is the one thing I'd push back on. It would make each step 3–4× the cost and add 30–90s of
  latency per tool call — reading a file, running a test, a one-line edit would each trigger a full panel. The article's gains are measured on complex
  research/decision tasks, not on mechanical steps. Beast-mode should fire on consequential decisions (what approach, what to change, did this pass), not  on every keystroke. Same quality lift, ~10× less waste.

  How I'd implement it in our harness

  The harness already has the exact primitives this needs — we'd be composing them, not inventing:

  - Workflow orchestration — does parallel agent() dispatch + a synthesis stage natively. This is literally the Fusion pipeline: parallel([panelA,
  panelB]) → judge → return. This is the engine.
  - A beast-mode toggle — same mechanism as your existing kill-switch (---/===): a prompt token or /beast writes .claude/state/beast-mode.flag; hooks
  read it.
  - A "fusion gate" — modeled on your pre-flight gate. When beast-mode is on and the main agent is about to take a consequential action, the gate routes
  the decision through a small fusion workflow and injects the synthesized recommendation back before the action proceeds.
  - A reusable fusion skill/script — panel(prompt, n=2, model=opus) → judge(prompt, responses) → synthesis, returning the structured
  consensus/contradictions/blind-spots object. Callable both by the gate and on demand.

  Two viable wiring strategies (this is the main fork):

  - A — Advisory injection (cheaper, safer): at decision points the main agent calls the fusion skill, gets the synthesized analysis, and proceeds. Like
  a smarter pre-flight. Low risk, easy to build, you stay in control.
  - B — Hard gate (closer to your literal description): a hook intercepts consequential actions, runs the panel+judge, and blocks until the synthesis is
  produced and acknowledged. Truest to "every action runs through subagents," but heavier and more brittle (latency, loops, cost).

