  "How do we deterministically decide what's a consequential action?"
  We don't infer it semantically — that would need an LLM judging intent, which is non-deterministic and exactly what our harness philosophy forbids ("a
  script checks whether…, never the agent must…"). Instead we classify on observable signals already present at the hook layer. A PreToolUse hook  receives the tool name and tool_input as stdin JSON. So "consequential" becomes a pure function of four deterministic inputs:

  1. Tool type (free, exact):
  - Read / Glob / Grep → never consequential. Skip.
  - Write / Edit → candidate.
  - Bash → consequential only if it matches the mutating/destructive regex set we already maintain in pre-bash-gate.sh (tee, sed -i, redirects, heredoc,
  cp/mv) — plus git commit|push, rm, deploy scripts.

  2. Target path (free, exact — lists already exist):
  - Bookkeeping paths (.claude/state/, .agent-memory/, contracts/, specs/, pre-flight/, agentwiki/) → not consequential. These are the same exemption
  lists every gate already carries.
  - Source code, the spec, the contract, git/deploy targets → consequential.

  3. Phase (free — state machine already tags it):
  - The genuinely consequential decisions cluster at phase boundaries, and those are already deterministic file events: writing product-spec.md (the PLAN  decision), finalizing the contract (NEGOTIATE), writing phase-complete-marker.md (a transition), the EVALUATE verdict. We fire fusion on those
  specific, named events.

  4. Debounce counter (free — the harness already counts writes; you can see "Writes: 1030"):
  - Fire at most once per file per phase (first touch), or every Nth qualifying write. This bounds cost deterministically instead of firing on every
  keystroke.

  So the deterministic rule is:

  ▎ Fusion fires iff: tool ∈ {Write, Edit} or Bash matches the mutate/destructive set — AND target path is not in the bookkeeping exemption list — AND 
  ▎ it's a source/decision artifact — AND the debounce gate allows it (first-touch / Nth / phase-transition).

  Plus an always-consequential set keyed purely by filename/command: phase-complete-marker.md, git commit|push, rm -rf, deploy scripts, contract
  finalization.

  The knobs (the path lists and N) are all editable config — you tighten or loosen "consequential" by editing lists, never by trusting a model. This is
  the same shape as the existing pre-flight/evidence gates, so it slots into machinery you already trust.

  Now my four answers (my recommendations)

  1. Trigger scope: Consequential-only, defined by the deterministic classifier above. "Every tool call" is technically possible with the same classifier  (just set the path list to * and N=1), but it's 3–4× cost on reads for no measured benefit. I'd ship consequential-only with "every call" as a config
  flag you can flip.
  2. Enforcement: Advisory injection first. The fusion runs, the synthesized analysis (consensus / contradictions / blind-spots) is injected back to the
  main agent, which then proceeds. It's lower-risk, easy to build on the Workflow engine, and you keep control. We design it so flipping to a hard
  blocking gate later is a one-line change — but blocking-on-every-action is where latency/loops bite, so prove value advisory-first.
  3. Panel: Opus-only (2× Opus 4.8 panel + 1× Opus 4.8 judge). The article's own result — Opus fused with itself jumping 58.8% → 65.5% — says the
  synthesis step delivers most of the lift with zero extra vendors or keys. Mixed-vendor/OpenRouter-Fusion-API are real upgrades, but they add keys,
  cost, and an external dependency; I'd make the panel a config list so you can add GPT/Gemini later without rework.
  4. Delivery: Build it in _install, shipped OFF by default behind the beast-mode.flag (kill-switch mechanism). That gives every project/server the
  capability while guaranteeing it never fires until you turn it on with /beast — same safety posture we used for headroom.

  The engine for all of this already exists: the Workflow tool does parallel([panelA, panelB]) → judge → synthesis natively, which is the Fusion
  pipeline. So beast-mode is mostly (a) the deterministic classifier hook + (b) a reusable fusion skill wrapping that workflow + (c) the flag/toggle.

